Rule 5: Be suspicious of links. If someone sends you a shortlink, try a shortlink expander. Better still is to get the name of the website and google it, and then click on the link in Google. It‚Äôs much harder to fool Google than it is to send a spoofed link.

Rule 4: Get a hardware wallet
Yes, it‚Äôs that important. Items stored in hardware wallets are more difficult to steal than items stored in browser wallets, because hardware wallets keep your private keys ‚Äúoffline‚Äù as long as the device isn‚Äôt plugged in to your computer.
Rule 3: Read rule 2 again.

Rule 2: Never, ever, ever, EVER, give your seed phrase to someone on the internet
Doesn‚Äôt matter if the person says they‚Äôre from a project‚Äôs Support Team. Doesn‚Äôt matter. DO. NOT. GIVE. YOUR. SEED. PHRASE. OUT. OVER. THE. INTERNET. EVER. Get it? Got it? Good.

Rule 1: Backup your seed phrase
You should think of your seed phrase as being ‚Äúyour money‚Äù. If you were the sole keeper of your money, would you just write down the secret password in one place? Hell no. Write it down in at least two different secure offline places.
